  <datafield tag="245" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Quantitative BT-Theorem and automatic continuity for standard von Neumann algebras</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="260" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="c">2016-02-05</subfield>
    <subfield code="t">published</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="300" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">25</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="520" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">We prove a general criterion for a von Neumann algebra M in order to be in standard form. It is formulated in terms of an everywhere defined, invertible, antilinear, a priori not necessarily bounded operator, intertwining M with its commutant <math altimg="si1.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msup><mrow><mi>M</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>′</mo></mrow></msup></math> and acting as the ⁎-operation on the centre. We also prove a generalized version of the BT-Theorem which enables us to see that such an intertwiner must be necessarily bounded. It is shown that this extension of the BT-Theorem leads to the automatic boundedness of quite general operators which intertwine the identity map of a von Neumann algebra with a general bounded, real-linear, operator-valued map. We apply the last result to the automatic boundedness of linear operators implementing algebraic morphisms of a von Neumann algebra onto some Banach algebra, and to the structure of a <math altimg="si2.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msup><mrow><mi>W</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>⁎</mo></mrow></msup></math> -algebra M endowed with a normal, semi-finite, faithful weight φ , whose left ideal <math altimg="si268.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant="fraktur">N</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>φ</mi></mrow></msub></math> admits an algebraic complement in the GNS representation space <math altimg="si283.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi>H</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>φ</mi></mrow></msub></math> , invariant under the canonical action of M .</subfield>
    <subfield code="9">Elsevier</subfield>
  </datafield>
